&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: Yeah.

00:00:37.500 --> 00:00:41.409
So, I mean, first of all, thanks so much for
having us and thanks, Julia, for--.

00:00:41.409 --> 00:00:43.260
I heard you were posting flyers all night.

00:00:43.260 --> 00:00:45.289
So, we're super appreciative for that.

00:00:45.289 --> 00:00:47.610
And thanks for some friends in the audience.

00:00:47.610 --> 00:00:50.090
It's good to see you guys.

00:00:50.090 --> 00:00:51.749
I guess we're really excited about sharing
this with you.

00:00:51.749 --> 00:00:54.100
So, I guess we'll just kind of kick it off.

00:00:54.100 --> 00:00:55.100
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: OK.

00:00:55.100 --> 00:01:00.270
We'll look at some pictures and speak generally
about the idea we're proposing here.

00:01:00.270 --> 00:01:05.080
But in a nutshell, and if you've seen, maybe
come across this in the media, it's oftentimes

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:10.800
been called the Low Line for some fairly obvious
reasons which you'll probably see in a second.

00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:17.900
But at the heart of it is a concept that we're
working on to build an underground park underneath

00:01:17.900 --> 00:01:21.830
the Lower East Side in an abandoned trolley
terminal.

00:01:21.830 --> 00:01:26.380
And it uses it innovative solar technology
to actually accomplish this.

00:01:26.380 --> 00:01:31.890
And we'd like to do is just walk through the
genesis of the idea, talk a little bit about

00:01:31.890 --> 00:01:36.640
how it works, talk about some of the design
issues, talk about the technology, too.

00:01:36.640 --> 00:01:42.470
And then, generally speak about the process
and maybe even have a very light Q and A,

00:01:42.470 --> 00:01:44.950
where you guys can just talk to us about it.

00:01:44.950 --> 00:01:46.650
All right.

00:01:46.650 --> 00:01:48.690
So, let's start here.

00:01:48.690 --> 00:01:50.070
All right.

00:01:50.070 --> 00:01:51.710
Does anyone here know who this guy is?

00:01:51.710 --> 00:01:53.270
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: Oh, come on.

00:01:53.270 --> 00:01:54.510
&gt;&gt;MALE #1: Shigeru Miyamoto.

00:01:54.510 --> 00:01:56.470
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: You're awesome.

00:01:56.470 --> 00:02:04.240
Shigeru Miyamoto, for those of you who do
not recognize this man, is an amazing fellow.

00:02:04.240 --> 00:02:08.030
He is the guy that invented Super Mario Brothers.

00:02:08.030 --> 00:02:14.540
And I'll explain why this is significant in
a second, but a couple years ago, the New

00:02:14.540 --> 00:02:21.990
Yorker wrote an article about Shigeru Miyamoto
and why it was that he designed such amazing

00:02:21.990 --> 00:02:23.220
video games.

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:27.740
And if you think about it, Super Mario Brothers
is really simple, right?

00:02:27.740 --> 00:02:33.060
It's just a 2-D world and you're a plumber
running around jumping on mushrooms and turtles.

00:02:33.060 --> 00:02:38.390
But it's laid out in such a way that what
seems like a very simple map that you're running

00:02:38.390 --> 00:02:42.130
around in actually has all these levels and
layers of complexity.

00:02:42.130 --> 00:02:44.960
It has all these secrets for you to discover.

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:49.319
Like for example, in this screen right here
I think, somewhere over on the left side of

00:02:49.319 --> 00:02:56.140
the screen, you can jump up, you hit a secret
brick and a beanstalk pops out or something

00:02:56.140 --> 00:02:57.330
like that.

00:02:57.330 --> 00:03:01.400
But anyway, throughout this game and also
another famous game that he created called

00:03:01.400 --> 00:03:07.690
"Legend of Zelda," they're sort of peppered
with all these tiny little details that make

00:03:07.690 --> 00:03:12.040
exploring it something that never quite feels
finished and gives it a level of complexity

00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:17.620
that make these things endlessly interesting
and something you want to play again and again

00:03:17.620 --> 00:03:19.250
and again.

00:03:19.250 --> 00:03:24.020
Quite literally in this picture, you can jump,
obviously, in the pipe over here.

00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:27.840
And you go down into this secret underworld.

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:35.710
So, the reason I'm talking about this is that
well, for one thing, this is New York, by

00:03:35.710 --> 00:03:36.750
the way.

00:03:36.750 --> 00:03:40.099
New York City is an amazing, amazing town.

00:03:40.099 --> 00:03:47.440
And I think that there is a similarity of
level of complexity in New York and also a

00:03:47.440 --> 00:03:49.260
lot of other cities of course.

00:03:49.260 --> 00:03:52.010
But this is the city I know best and the city
I love the most.

00:03:52.010 --> 00:03:57.810
And every once in a while, New York City will,
like Super Mario Brothers, just peel back

00:03:57.810 --> 00:04:03.620
a layer of the onion and just give you a tiny
little glimpse into how amazingly complex

00:04:03.620 --> 00:04:07.860
it actually is and how many secrets it's still
hiding from you.

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:14.680
And that's one of the most compelling things,
to me anyway, about urbanism in New York.

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:16.090
It makes me wanna live here.

00:04:16.090 --> 00:04:19.130
It makes me endlessly fascinated with the
city.

00:04:19.130 --> 00:04:21.959
And I think it's an extremely powerful quality.

00:04:21.959 --> 00:04:31.080
Now, I think recently we've had this age in
which they've knocked down a lot of stuff--and

00:04:31.080 --> 00:04:37.590
no offense if this is your apartment building
or the Starbuck's that you really enjoy frequenting--I'm

00:04:37.590 --> 00:04:40.780
just using it as an example.

00:04:40.780 --> 00:04:43.840
But recently, they've knocked down a lot of
stuff.

00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:48.240
They've taken away a lot of our historical
legacy--all these little, quirky things.

00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:54.880
And actually, now that I think of it, you
guys have enabled Maps functions and Search

00:04:54.880 --> 00:05:00.230
functions that have really taken away a lot
of surprises out of the world and a lot of

00:05:00.230 --> 00:05:02.790
the mystery out of our cities.

00:05:02.790 --> 00:05:04.000
I'm not saying that's a bad thing.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.510
It's just a reality.

00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:13.180
However, you can have this landscape still
co-exist with some of these secrets I'm referring

00:05:13.180 --> 00:05:14.180
to.

00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:16.280
For example, just down the street from my
apartment.

00:05:16.280 --> 00:05:20.020
I live on Renwick Street, which by the way
in and of itself, is kind of a secret.

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:22.340
No one knows where Renwick Street is.

00:05:22.340 --> 00:05:25.030
But it's over near the Holland Tunnel.

00:05:25.030 --> 00:05:30.750
And if you are walking down the sidewalk and
staring at your feet, which one day I was,

00:05:30.750 --> 00:05:33.770
you will notice that there's this little sign
there.

00:05:33.770 --> 00:05:40.220
And I'm not gonna read it, but effectively
it says, hear ye, hear ye, here was ye olde

00:05:40.220 --> 00:05:41.930
waterfront of New York City.

00:05:41.930 --> 00:05:47.660
And this is where the sailboats and all these
masted ships used to pull up.

00:05:47.660 --> 00:05:51.820
And actually embedded in the sidewalk right
there, are these wooden piles just right there

00:05:51.820 --> 00:05:52.820
in the sidewalk.

00:05:52.820 --> 00:05:57.560
And you would never really notice this unless
you happened to have glanced at it or if you

00:05:57.560 --> 00:05:59.270
happened to know it was there.

00:05:59.270 --> 00:06:03.330
But I guess the point of all this is that
it's still there.

00:06:03.330 --> 00:06:06.990
And you have to know where to look.

00:06:06.990 --> 00:06:12.500
But New York will still find a way to surprise
you with its hidden complexities.

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:20.830
And New York is not so much like other East
Coast older cities, like Boston or Philadelphia

00:06:20.830 --> 00:06:24.960
for example, where they're really wearing
their history on their sleeve.

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:29.530
You actually have to seek it out a little
but in New York because we are so market-driven

00:06:29.530 --> 00:06:30.530
and forward-looking.

00:06:30.530 --> 00:06:37.640
But every once in a while, again, there's
certain places if you know where to look.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:39.580
And this is quite literally one of them.

00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:43.410
I don't know if anyone had the good fortune
to have done this.

00:06:43.410 --> 00:06:48.710
But this is Atlantic Avenue in front of Trader
Joe's in downtown Brooklyn.

00:06:48.710 --> 00:06:56.190
And underneath, inside one manhole cover,
you can go down it and that's what's in there.

00:06:56.190 --> 00:06:58.910
So, this is actually down there.

00:06:58.910 --> 00:07:04.470
It was a secret abandoned railroad tunnel
built in the 1840s.

00:07:04.470 --> 00:07:12.180
And some guy--just some random guy--it was
this self-trained history buff, right?

00:07:12.180 --> 00:07:14.520
Went down a manhole cover one day in the late-80s.

00:07:14.520 --> 00:07:19.330
I think it was the day after Indiana Jones
and the Temple of Doom came out.

00:07:19.330 --> 00:07:22.110
And he went down in here and he was like,
"Oh, my God.

00:07:22.110 --> 00:07:23.110
Look what I found."

00:07:23.110 --> 00:07:24.650
And lo and behold, there it is.

00:07:24.650 --> 00:07:25.650
It's huge.

00:07:25.650 --> 00:07:28.430
It goes all the way from Trader Joe's all
the way to the water.

00:07:28.430 --> 00:07:31.840
But I guess this is to illustrate a point
that it's down there.

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:36.500
And in general, we have this vast underworld
lurking underneath the service of New York.

00:07:36.500 --> 00:07:39.740
I mean, other cities of course as well, especially
European cities.

00:07:39.740 --> 00:07:42.100
But we have this vast underworld lurking down
there.

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:45.919
We have something like, and I don't think
it's all cataloged, but we have something

00:07:45.919 --> 00:07:50.840
like 13 acres of unused underground space
underneath New York.

00:07:50.840 --> 00:07:53.930
That's a lot in New York, by the way.

00:07:53.930 --> 00:07:59.080
So, here is maybe a less impressive one that's
over on, I think, Worth Street or something

00:07:59.080 --> 00:08:00.080
like that.

00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:04.900
And of course, this is the beautiful City
Hall Station.

00:08:04.900 --> 00:08:11.479
If anyone has snoozed on the 6 train or been
reading a book and forgot to get off at the

00:08:11.479 --> 00:08:15.700
last stop, at the Brooklyn Bridge stop, the
train will then circle around and loop around

00:08:15.700 --> 00:08:17.320
to go back uptown.

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:22.490
And if you wake up for just that instant in
a panic from being stuck on the train, this

00:08:22.490 --> 00:08:24.160
is probably what you'll see.

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:27.750
So, I'm not sure whether you're allowed to
be doing that, but if you have the chance,

00:08:27.750 --> 00:08:29.920
it's pretty cool.

00:08:29.920 --> 00:08:36.610
And I guess more specifically, this is the
space that we're looking at today.

00:08:36.610 --> 00:08:44.010
Actually, I'll hand the clicker over to Dan,
but this is the Williamsburg Trolley Terminal,

00:08:44.010 --> 00:08:46.420
built in 1903 and abandoned in 1948.

00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:48.360
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: Yeah.

00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:55.620
And James and in his work as an architect
and designer came across this site by befriending

00:08:55.620 --> 00:09:00.770
a former MTA engineer, who got him interested
in this particular location, which is just

00:09:00.770 --> 00:09:03.520
a couple blocks away from his office on the
Lower East Side.

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:09.860
And James and I, just by way of introduction,
started talking about this particular project

00:09:09.860 --> 00:09:16.520
because of my personal love and interest of
the subway and the city in general, but also

00:09:16.520 --> 00:09:20.380
I was separately thinking about an idea of
how we would potentially bring art into the

00:09:20.380 --> 00:09:21.890
underground subway.

00:09:21.890 --> 00:09:25.080
James had an entirely different angle, which
we'll get to actually, and is at the heart

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:26.300
of the actual project.

00:09:26.300 --> 00:09:31.570
But this actual location, as you can see here,
there's a couple of fun details in this picture.

00:09:31.570 --> 00:09:34.300
If you look--I think it's blown up enough--you
can see all the way in the back there some

00:09:34.300 --> 00:09:37.870
people in topcoats and they sort of look old-timey.

00:09:37.870 --> 00:09:40.410
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: They're probably mustachioed
as well.

00:09:40.410 --> 00:09:41.470
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: Mustachioed.

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:43.610
So, this is from the 1930s.

00:09:43.610 --> 00:09:50.100
And essentially what you're looking at is,
this is the trolley turnaround back in the

00:09:50.100 --> 00:09:53.680
days when the city used street cars primarily
to get around the city before the subways

00:09:53.680 --> 00:09:56.720
were really the main way that people got around
the city.

00:09:56.720 --> 00:10:01.580
And so, the trolleys would come over the Williamsburg
Bridge--and for those of you who are familiar

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:07.130
with this part of town, they would go underground
and this is essentially the terminal where

00:10:07.130 --> 00:10:11.410
the cars would be stored, turn around, go
back over the bridge.

00:10:11.410 --> 00:10:15.120
This is what it looks like today, actually.

00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:21.160
We're able to hoodwink the MTA into a tour,
which is a lot harder than it sounds, and

00:10:21.160 --> 00:10:26.850
when we got down there, we were really blown
away by the height, the scale of what you

00:10:26.850 --> 00:10:28.380
can see down there.

00:10:28.380 --> 00:10:32.240
Just again, sort of a sense of scale, you
can see that figure way, way, way in the back

00:10:32.240 --> 00:10:33.240
in the center.

00:10:33.240 --> 00:10:34.519
That's actually an MTA employee.

00:10:34.519 --> 00:10:37.140
So, it's just this incredibly massive space.

00:10:37.140 --> 00:10:39.380
It was wet 'cause there had just been a snowstorm.

00:10:39.380 --> 00:10:40.870
And so there's a lot of runoff.

00:10:40.870 --> 00:10:44.580
These are some more pictures of the location.

00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:51.670
It's actually directly adjacent to the JMZ
line, if you guys take the JMZ and when you're

00:10:51.670 --> 00:10:56.120
facing it to Brooklyn, you can actually see--.

00:10:56.120 --> 00:10:57.120
We had a photo.

00:10:57.120 --> 00:10:58.120
It's not there.

00:10:58.120 --> 00:10:59.120
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: It's the one after that.

00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:00.120
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: The one after?

00:11:00.120 --> 00:11:01.430
I'll show you in a sec.

00:11:01.430 --> 00:11:06.310
So, if you're actually on the JMZ track, you
can actually look into the location.

00:11:06.310 --> 00:11:11.600
And usually it's not lit, so it's this dark
expanse, but when it's lit you can see into

00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:13.089
the location.

00:11:13.089 --> 00:11:14.330
One of the incredible things that--.

00:11:14.330 --> 00:11:16.519
This is a photo that we actually took during
our tour.

00:11:16.519 --> 00:11:20.459
There's remnant cobblestone, remnant rail
lines, and it is the kind of that you get

00:11:20.459 --> 00:11:23.970
down there--and James just talked about it--it's
like an Indiana Jones moment.

00:11:23.970 --> 00:11:28.149
It's this incredibly exciting discovery almost
of this abandoned space.

00:11:28.149 --> 00:11:31.350
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: I also felt like it was the
scene in Lord of the Rings where they go into

00:11:31.350 --> 00:11:32.350
the dwarf mine.

00:11:32.350 --> 00:11:33.740
I don't know if anyone saw it.

00:11:33.740 --> 00:11:34.740
Very similar.

00:11:34.740 --> 00:11:37.000
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: That's kind of what it was
like.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:41.610
So, this is the location for those of you
who may or may not be familiar with the neighborhood.

00:11:41.610 --> 00:11:42.920
One the left there--.

00:11:42.920 --> 00:11:44.500
This is actually Google Maps.

00:11:44.500 --> 00:11:46.790
So, it's pretty awesome.

00:11:46.790 --> 00:11:50.010
The yellow over there is the Williamsburg
Bridge.

00:11:50.010 --> 00:11:53.459
And this is where Delancey Street ends and
when the Brooklyn Bridge starts.

00:11:53.459 --> 00:11:55.340
So, it's directly below.

00:11:55.340 --> 00:11:59.019
That's Delancey Street and it's that weird,
little hook there.

00:11:59.019 --> 00:12:02.330
If you guys are familiar with Delancey Street
and you ever wondered why there's all that

00:12:02.330 --> 00:12:06.350
weird, wasted space to the right when you're
facing the bridge, it's actually because of

00:12:06.350 --> 00:12:10.230
the existence of this underground space that
most people don't know about.

00:12:10.230 --> 00:12:19.790
Here's an old drawing from probably the turn
of the century of what the bridge may have

00:12:19.790 --> 00:12:22.670
looked like back in its earlier days.

00:12:22.670 --> 00:12:27.730
As I mentioned, the Williamsburg Bridge was
built in 1903 and obviously the trolley terminal

00:12:27.730 --> 00:12:31.290
was built at the same time.

00:12:31.290 --> 00:12:36.600
These are some other fun pictures of Delancey
Street in the 1930s.

00:12:36.600 --> 00:12:45.760
And this is, you can see a lot of the elevated
track lines and a bustling streetscape.

00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:52.790
But I think what's compelling about this is
you can see that it had a vibrant night life--,

00:12:52.790 --> 00:13:00.130
streetscape, and it also has, as the Lower
East Side has always been, this crossroads

00:13:00.130 --> 00:13:04.589
from a transportation perspective, but also
just culturally and from a merchant perspective

00:13:04.589 --> 00:13:06.329
as well.

00:13:06.329 --> 00:13:13.730
Which I think brings us to the current day
and again, this is a view from the Williamsburg

00:13:13.730 --> 00:13:14.730
Bridge.

00:13:14.730 --> 00:13:18.990
And you can see, actually, that there's a
really limited amount of green space in the

00:13:18.990 --> 00:13:19.990
area.

00:13:19.990 --> 00:13:27.100
You can see also that it's a space that is
friendly to cars, but is actually pretty challenging

00:13:27.100 --> 00:13:29.540
for cyclists and for pedestrians.

00:13:29.540 --> 00:13:34.810
It's one of the most dangerous parts of the
city from a cyclist and pedestrian perspective.

00:13:34.810 --> 00:13:39.870
There was just a little girl who was actually
killed, unfortunately, walking across the

00:13:39.870 --> 00:13:42.320
street just a couple weeks ago.

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:47.800
And it remains this large transportation question,
but also this livability question for the

00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:51.810
neighborhood--how to make this particular
neighborhood, this particular node of the

00:13:51.810 --> 00:13:54.380
city greener and more livable.

00:13:54.380 --> 00:14:01.370
So, one of the answers to why this is the
case is the actual history of New York City.

00:14:01.370 --> 00:14:04.570
And I don't know if you guys have been to
exhibit at the Museum of the City of New York,

00:14:04.570 --> 00:14:15.170
but there's a really fun exhibit on the grid
and its creation of blocks--very geometric

00:14:15.170 --> 00:14:17.290
blocks that span across the entire city.

00:14:17.290 --> 00:14:21.310
And what those do is they're very efficient
from a real estate perspective and are designed

00:14:21.310 --> 00:14:27.220
really for optimal economic output, but they
aren't really conducive to green space and

00:14:27.220 --> 00:14:32.840
don't really allow for some of the sweeping
green spaces in parks that you see in less

00:14:32.840 --> 00:14:37.470
gridded cities like many of the European capitals.

00:14:37.470 --> 00:14:42.440
This is one of the images that we actually
have some across in our research and our zeal

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:48.170
for this project in a book called "How the
Other Half Lives," which is a really incredible

00:14:48.170 --> 00:14:53.329
book on the history of the Lower East Side,
specifically in some of its darkest and most

00:14:53.329 --> 00:14:58.899
dangerous and uncertain times in the 19th
Century actually.

00:14:58.899 --> 00:15:04.660
And here what you see is a somewhat disturbing
image of a bunch of kids in an obviously very

