00:30:56.779 --> 00:30:58.649
I don't work here.

00:30:58.649 --> 00:31:03.419
&gt;&gt;MALE #2: I haven't been keeping up with
it, but I remember a few months ago the Department

00:31:03.419 --> 00:31:06.389
of Transportation was talking about doing
a lot of construction on Delancey, the way

00:31:06.389 --> 00:31:08.289
the bridge connects with Delancey.

00:31:08.289 --> 00:31:12.309
Putting up a big wall, basically, perpendicular
to the bridge.

00:31:12.309 --> 00:31:14.299
Does that conflict at all with what you're
doing?

00:31:14.299 --> 00:31:15.659
Is that still happening?

00:31:15.659 --> 00:31:19.909
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: The proposal that he's referring
to has to do with the way that bikes come

00:31:19.909 --> 00:31:21.690
down off of the bridge.

00:31:21.690 --> 00:31:24.919
And I think it's safe here to say this.

00:31:24.919 --> 00:31:29.309
I think it's a bonehead idea 'cause say you
are zooming down the bridge at like, Mach

00:31:29.309 --> 00:31:32.339
Two, and then there's a concrete wall right
in front of you, right?

00:31:32.339 --> 00:31:33.339
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;MALE #2: Yeah.

00:31:33.339 --> 00:31:35.209
That's a popular opinion, I've heard.

00:31:35.209 --> 00:31:41.839
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: I mean, I think more to the
point, it does highlight that there is a pretty

00:31:41.839 --> 00:31:44.129
hardcore circulation issue at that point.

00:31:44.129 --> 00:31:49.509
I think that basically they built a corridor,
specifically based on cars and trucks.

00:31:49.509 --> 00:31:54.719
And everything else is just an afterthought,
including human beings and bicycles.

00:31:54.719 --> 00:32:00.379
And so, for anyone who's been hurtling down
that bridge, you're just unceremoniously dropped

00:32:00.379 --> 00:32:04.289
at the end of the bridge into Delancey Street
traffic, which is, as we know, some of the

00:32:04.289 --> 00:32:06.110
most dangerous in the city.

00:32:06.110 --> 00:32:12.009
So, I think it's admirable that they are proposing
a solution to try and protect the bikers from

00:32:12.009 --> 00:32:13.099
the car traffic.

00:32:13.099 --> 00:32:17.649
I think that's a great step in the right direction.

00:32:17.649 --> 00:32:22.839
We see this project as potentially posing
other solutions to that bike circulation issue

00:32:22.839 --> 00:32:26.869
that who's repercussions we had ourselves
thought through all the way.

00:32:26.869 --> 00:32:32.149
But we would hope that this addresses some
of those circulation issues directly.

00:32:32.149 --> 00:32:34.720
&gt;&gt;MALE #2: Yeah, if you could be like, an
alternative to that, that'd be--.

00:32:34.720 --> 00:32:36.080
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: I mean, wouldn't that be cool?

00:32:36.080 --> 00:32:37.080
Zoom down into there, reemerge.

00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:38.080
You know, something like that.

00:32:38.080 --> 00:32:39.080
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #1: Hey, how are you?

00:32:39.080 --> 00:32:40.080
So, really cool technology.

00:32:40.080 --> 00:32:41.080
Really awesome idea.

00:32:41.080 --> 00:32:42.080
How much do you guys think it's gonna cost?

00:32:42.080 --> 00:32:43.080
And where do you think the money's gonna come
from?

00:32:43.080 --> 00:32:44.080
'Cause I'm assuming that the MTA does this.

00:32:44.080 --> 00:32:45.080
That the MTA doesn’t have that much money
right now and probably wants to make a lot

00:32:45.080 --> 00:32:46.080
of money on any purchase of what they own.

00:32:46.080 --> 00:32:47.080
Is it--?

00:32:47.080 --> 00:32:48.080
Are they looking to sell the city?

00:32:48.080 --> 00:32:49.080
I mean, what kind of estimates do you guys
have about how much it's gonna cost?

00:32:49.080 --> 00:32:57.570
Besides the technology, there's obviously
a big clean-up and then the safety issues

00:32:57.570 --> 00:33:15.039
and then making it sanitary and all those
kinds of things after a hundred years.

00:33:15.039 --> 00:33:18.539
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: Right.

00:33:18.539 --> 00:33:20.619
Plus getting into it and getting a wheelchair,
etcetera.

00:33:20.619 --> 00:33:21.619
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #1: Right.

00:33:21.619 --> 00:33:22.619
All of those types of things.

00:33:22.619 --> 00:33:26.820
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: See, you pretty much nailed
why this is an amazing challenge, right?

00:33:26.820 --> 00:33:27.820
[laughter]

00:33:27.820 --> 00:33:30.190
And why we're spending all our time on this.

00:33:30.190 --> 00:33:31.789
So, you're right.

00:33:31.789 --> 00:33:34.019
So, just to address all of the different elements
there.

00:33:34.019 --> 00:33:36.919
The MTA owns the space.

00:33:36.919 --> 00:33:42.220
The MTA, you may have heard, is an agency
that is billions of dollars in debt.

00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:47.210
And is looking to liquidate all its real estate
as much as it can.

00:33:47.210 --> 00:33:50.950
This is obviously a location, interestingly,
that wasn't on the radar before we had started

00:33:50.950 --> 00:33:51.950
talking about it.

00:33:51.950 --> 00:33:56.070
And now, it's a much more interesting and
people have heard of the location over the

00:33:56.070 --> 00:33:57.130
last few months.

00:33:57.130 --> 00:33:59.619
We've been working really closely with the
MTA.

00:33:59.619 --> 00:34:02.830
I'm understanding a little bit more about
what kinds of thresholds they would need in

00:34:02.830 --> 00:34:06.679
order for us to submit the competing bid.

00:34:06.679 --> 00:34:11.100
And there's a lot of people, both in the MTA
and outside the MTA, who think this is a wonderful

00:34:11.100 --> 00:34:14.429
idea and are basically saying, "We give you
all of our support.

00:34:14.429 --> 00:34:17.529
Essentially what you need to do is you need
to go and raise money."

00:34:17.529 --> 00:34:22.440
And so, what we've done is we've set up a
501(c)3 non-profit organization, very similar

00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:28.519
to the High Line, and again, taking a lot
of advice from the High Line founders on where

00:34:28.519 --> 00:34:30.230
some of that money would come from.

00:34:30.230 --> 00:34:36.480
So, we have a range of ways that we've benchmarked
how the cost would be.

00:34:36.480 --> 00:34:39.769
It's all conjecture at this point because
there's so many questions we don't know around

00:34:39.769 --> 00:34:42.070
what's gonna happen above ground.

00:34:42.070 --> 00:34:46.270
We have a range of engineers and legal experts
and folks who are gonna help us come up with

00:34:46.270 --> 00:34:49.179
a number that's actually a lot more realistic
and then will probably have to get thrown

00:34:49.179 --> 00:34:50.179
away.

00:34:50.179 --> 00:34:53.579
Interestingly, the High Line guys came up
with a number on how much it was gonna cost

00:34:53.579 --> 00:34:59.829
them, that they were way off on and they realized
that only several years further into the process.

00:34:59.829 --> 00:35:00.829
So,--.

00:35:00.829 --> 00:35:02.241
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #1: They were under?

00:35:02.241 --> 00:35:04.750
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: They were under significantly
actually, yeah.

00:35:04.750 --> 00:35:08.520
But what the High Line guys--I think they're
really inspiring in a lot of ways--that what

00:35:08.520 --> 00:35:11.920
they've proven to be is fund-raising juggernauts.

00:35:11.920 --> 00:35:18.740
And what they've been able to do is to do
a mix of, if anyone has worked in or worked

00:35:18.740 --> 00:35:25.039
with non-profits, it's a mix of a standard
non-profit fund-raising model of private donations,

00:35:25.039 --> 00:35:32.900
corporate support, Google would be a wonderful
supporter, and foundation support.

00:35:32.900 --> 00:35:36.570
And the High Line eventually also moved to
a membership-based model.

00:35:36.570 --> 00:35:38.690
So, there's another fund-raising stream there,
too.

00:35:38.690 --> 00:35:40.420
They've done all kinds of other interesting
things, too.

00:35:40.420 --> 00:35:47.990
I mean, another interesting dimension of this
is that the neighborhood is extremely excited

00:35:47.990 --> 00:35:54.970
about this as a business opportunity for existing
and new businesses.

00:35:54.970 --> 00:36:00.599
The Lower East Side business district has
just actually officially endorsed us as our

00:36:00.599 --> 00:36:02.480
representative on the city council.

00:36:02.480 --> 00:36:07.160
And I think those two votes of support point
to the fact that the local business community

00:36:07.160 --> 00:36:13.690
actually feels that this would be a tremendous
magnet and an important economic boon for

00:36:13.690 --> 00:36:17.380
a neighborhood that often is where you go
to get drunk at night, but is actually not

00:36:17.380 --> 00:36:24.020
necessarily a vibrant, deeply integrated business
community that others from other neighborhoods

00:36:24.020 --> 00:36:27.670
and other countries and other cities come
to when they come to New York City.

00:36:27.670 --> 00:36:34.140
So, the High Line has proven its tremendous
economic impact.

00:36:34.140 --> 00:36:39.110
The numbers that are circling in my head is
that at this point, it's cost about 250 million

00:36:39.110 --> 00:36:41.309
dollars to get the High Line to where it is
now.

00:36:41.309 --> 00:36:46.920
But they've generated about two billion dollars
in value for the city and for the economy.

00:36:46.920 --> 00:36:50.619
So, and that will only continue and grow over
time.

00:36:50.619 --> 00:36:54.180
So, there's a larger story that we need to
be able to tell.

00:36:54.180 --> 00:36:59.220
And a big part of what we're doing this year
is doing the research we need to be able to

00:36:59.220 --> 00:37:02.319
land at some compelling numbers, not only
around cost, but also around the potentials

00:37:02.319 --> 00:37:05.400
or benefit to the city.

00:37:05.400 --> 00:37:09.359
Anyone want to step up to the mic?

00:37:09.359 --> 00:37:11.670
&gt;&gt;MALE #3: Sure.

00:37:11.670 --> 00:37:16.140
What kind of environmental remediation is
gonna need to be done on the site?

00:37:16.140 --> 00:37:17.619
I mean, is it lead paint everywhere?

00:37:17.619 --> 00:37:18.670
Is it more than that?

00:37:18.670 --> 00:37:23.760
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: Well, Dan actually, in addressing
the previous question, brought up the issue

00:37:23.760 --> 00:37:28.839
of needing more information about what the
general costs of this overall project to construct

00:37:28.839 --> 00:37:30.460
would actually be.

00:37:30.460 --> 00:37:36.500
And I think you bring up a very valid and
interesting point, but until we actually get

00:37:36.500 --> 00:37:41.510
a team of engineers, cleared by the MTA, to
go down into there and start exploring some

00:37:41.510 --> 00:37:45.240
of the environmental conditions, it would
be difficult to say right off the bat.

00:37:45.240 --> 00:37:49.099
I mean, look, dollars to donuts, there's probably
lead paint down there, right?

00:37:49.099 --> 00:37:51.589
I mean, it's from 1903 for God's sake.

00:37:51.589 --> 00:37:57.360
There's also drainage that needs to happen
and who knows what else.

00:37:57.360 --> 00:38:02.769
I think what's working in our favor is the
fact that it was basically forgotten about

00:38:02.769 --> 00:38:04.150
after 1943.

00:38:04.150 --> 00:38:08.470
And there's just been nothing in there except
maybe the occasional mole person, right?

00:38:08.470 --> 00:38:14.740
So, any sort of environmental issues that
might be at play with the space itself would

00:38:14.740 --> 00:38:20.630
be ones that are created from the original
construction, like you say, from the lead

00:38:20.630 --> 00:38:22.160
paint, for example.

00:38:22.160 --> 00:38:23.270
[pause]

00:38:23.270 --> 00:38:26.620
&gt;&gt;MALE #4: Hi.

00:38:26.620 --> 00:38:28.059
I love the idea.

00:38:28.059 --> 00:38:31.170
I saw this about six months ago and I thought
it was fantastic then.

00:38:31.170 --> 00:38:32.829
I still think it's fantastic.

00:38:32.829 --> 00:38:36.370
I had a question about the scale of it, though.

00:38:36.370 --> 00:38:38.809
So, in these drawings, you modeled this all
out.

00:38:38.809 --> 00:38:41.269
How large are the collectors?

00:38:41.269 --> 00:38:43.250
How many of them do you need?

00:38:43.250 --> 00:38:46.630
And where do you plan to put them above ground?

00:38:46.630 --> 00:38:49.440
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: Well, let's talk about two
things.

00:38:49.440 --> 00:38:52.250
First of all, the space itself, I don't think
we got to this little factoid.

00:38:52.250 --> 00:38:58.480
But the space itself is about 60 thousand
square feet, which is roughly equivalent in

00:38:58.480 --> 00:39:01.579
size to the first leg of the High Line when
they built that.

00:39:01.579 --> 00:39:06.141
It's also roughly equivalent in size to--this
is a terrible comparison--to two-thirds of

00:39:06.141 --> 00:39:09.890
the size of Gramercy Park.

00:39:09.890 --> 00:39:13.789
But I guess the case in point being, it is
a pretty large space.

00:39:13.789 --> 00:39:18.980
Now, when you set up a technology like this--light
goes in, light goes out--you don't get to

00:39:18.980 --> 00:39:19.980
save it.

00:39:19.980 --> 00:39:23.150
You don't get to build it up or anything like
that.

00:39:23.150 --> 00:39:24.680
Purely optical device.

00:39:24.680 --> 00:39:28.289
So, in a vacuum, let's say you have a square
meter of collection.

00:39:28.289 --> 00:39:30.320
You put in a hundred thousand lumens.

00:39:30.320 --> 00:39:32.160
You have a distributer downstairs.

00:39:32.160 --> 00:39:36.290
So, square meter in a vacuum, a hundred thousand
lumens comes out.

00:39:36.290 --> 00:39:38.369
Of course, it's not gonna be a hundred percent
efficient.

00:39:38.369 --> 00:39:41.880
You'll probably lose 20 percent of the light,
which is fine.

00:39:41.880 --> 00:39:48.369
But, I guess, point being, you need to manage
how much light is going to be delivered to

00:39:48.369 --> 00:39:53.609
certain areas as a design concept really and
based on what the light requirements of the

00:39:53.609 --> 00:39:56.569
various plantings are actually gonna be.

00:39:56.569 --> 00:40:02.859
So, without going into detail about the design
of the plantings and the landscape architecture,

00:40:02.859 --> 00:40:06.789
it's difficult to say how much light you actually
need to deliver down there.

00:40:06.789 --> 00:40:14.059
However, just my initial back of the napkin
projections in math indicate to me that for

00:40:14.059 --> 00:40:19.640
one thing, I think these things want to live
on the elevated median that's currently in

00:40:19.640 --> 00:40:21.359
the middle of Delancey Street.

00:40:21.359 --> 00:40:23.570
It's on the north side of the site.

00:40:23.570 --> 00:40:28.990
It will not fall into the shadows of the proposed
development that's going up to the south.

00:40:28.990 --> 00:40:35.950
And it's an appropriate path for the lighting
to actually go filter through.

00:40:35.950 --> 00:40:40.710
Now, as for the number of collectors that
we're talking about, I mean, it will depend

00:40:40.710 --> 00:40:43.890
of course on how much light you need to deliver
down into the space.

00:40:43.890 --> 00:40:49.720
But as far as arrays go, I would say probably
something like 30 or 40 of them or something

00:40:49.720 --> 00:40:51.500
like that.

00:40:51.500 --> 00:40:55.170
And of course, you can calibrate how much
light is getting in there by how much you

00:40:55.170 --> 00:40:56.170
need, and therefore, what you need on the
topside, etc.

00:40:56.170 --> 00:40:57.170
So,--.

00:40:57.170 --> 00:40:58.170
&gt;&gt;MALE #4: Thank you.

00:40:58.170 --> 00:40:59.170
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #2: Do you have a sense of, you mentioned
MTA was opening up this space for proposal.

00:40:59.170 --> 00:41:03.680
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: Yeah.

00:41:03.680 --> 00:41:11.210
&gt;&gt;FEMALE #2: Who else is interested in it?

00:41:11.210 --> 00:41:12.210
And how many other people--?

00:41:12.210 --> 00:41:13.210
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: It's just gonna be the world's
biggest Red Lobster.

00:41:13.210 --> 00:41:14.210
[laughter]

00:41:14.210 --> 00:41:16.880
And we're really gonna have to duke it out
with them.

00:41:16.880 --> 00:41:19.470
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: Actually, that's really funny.

00:41:19.470 --> 00:41:23.079
We had extreme fun of presenting this to a
high school yesterday morning.

00:41:23.079 --> 00:41:26.790
And I think one of the kids said something
like, "Could this be a McDonald's?"

00:41:26.790 --> 00:41:28.079
’Cause that would be really cool."

00:41:28.079 --> 00:41:29.079
[laughter]

00:41:29.079 --> 00:41:33.000
I think that's actually exactly what we're
trying not to do.

00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:36.660
And so, they also demanded Wi-Fi, which I
thought was really funny.

00:41:36.660 --> 00:41:38.059
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: Like, all of them demanded
Wi-Fi.

00:41:38.059 --> 00:41:39.059
Five bars.

00:41:39.059 --> 00:41:42.250
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: Right, all the time.

00:41:42.250 --> 00:41:44.470
And your iPhone will work down there.

00:41:44.470 --> 00:41:48.720
But I think that we really don't know.

00:41:48.720 --> 00:41:53.031
I think that the site is going to get more
and more interesting over the course of this

00:41:53.031 --> 00:41:55.510
year if we have anything to say about it.

00:41:55.510 --> 00:42:01.369
And I think that what we're trying to do is
to drive forward a sense that we are the folks

00:42:01.369 --> 00:42:03.640
who are actually focused on the community.

00:42:03.640 --> 00:42:08.680
And when other developers come to the table,
as they almost definitely will, who are interested

00:42:08.680 --> 00:42:14.150
in doing interesting things or things that
have heavy retail component, that we actually

00:42:14.150 --> 00:42:18.859
will be able to say actually we've spent the
time talking to the community about what it

00:42:18.859 --> 00:42:24.960
wants to do and this isn't simply a conversation
around short-term gain for MTA, but there

00:42:24.960 --> 00:42:29.250
are other factors at play and there's a community
here and there's people who actually need

00:42:29.250 --> 00:42:30.910
some green space.

00:42:30.910 --> 00:42:32.630
So, I think that's where we're coming from.

00:42:32.630 --> 00:42:38.180
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: You know it's funny that the
irony here is that, just broadly speaking,

00:42:38.180 --> 00:42:42.950
the reason that you don't find so much green
space in any New York neighborhood is because

00:42:42.950 --> 00:42:49.099
there exists this very focused market-driven
mentality, well, throughout the city.

00:42:49.099 --> 00:42:55.720
And so, setting aside a piece of land for
just general public use is, it's a very rare

00:42:55.720 --> 00:42:57.549
thing in this town.

00:42:57.549 --> 00:42:58.549
And so, here we are.

00:42:58.549 --> 00:43:02.890
And we discover a giant space that no one
even knew about, all these square feet.

00:43:02.890 --> 00:43:04.650
And now all of a sudden, it's like, OK.

00:43:04.650 --> 00:43:11.570
So, we've gotta look at this competitive development
schemes to generate money from this thing.

00:43:11.570 --> 00:43:14.450
I think that's, of course, it's fair to say
it's not our space.

00:43:14.450 --> 00:43:16.390
It's the MTA's space.

00:43:16.390 --> 00:43:21.970
We would very much like to build them an economic
model that actually shows that this thing

00:43:21.970 --> 00:43:23.589
can actually turn a profit as well.

00:43:23.589 --> 00:43:28.680
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: Actually, I mean, on that point,
the High Line is a recent example of something

00:43:28.680 --> 00:43:32.380
that, in our lifetime, actually for most of
us who have been in New York throughout the

00:43:32.380 --> 00:43:37.470
entire process, a group of individuals who
are just from the community decided to say,

00:43:37.470 --> 00:43:43.100
"We actually want to fight to turn this, to
A, not tear it down and B, turn it into an

00:43:43.100 --> 00:43:46.970
actual, public space that's free, that's green,
that's beautiful."

00:43:46.970 --> 00:43:52.190
And actually, in New York City's history,
most of the parks and green spaces in the

00:43:52.190 --> 00:43:59.020
city happened that way, either through community
activism or through the creation of a private-led

00:43:59.020 --> 00:44:00.020
park.

00:44:00.020 --> 00:44:04.359
So, even looking at things like the saving
of Grand Central was something where a bunch

00:44:04.359 --> 00:44:09.609
of pissed off people said, "We really want
this to be saved," and not turned into something

00:44:09.609 --> 00:44:12.630
that isn't stunning, beautiful, and for the
public.

00:44:12.630 --> 00:44:17.829
So, I think the examples of that go all the
way through New York City's history.

00:44:17.829 --> 00:44:23.070
And the interesting thing is obviously just
that the Park's Department just announced

00:44:23.070 --> 00:44:25.150
a budget cut yesterday.

00:44:25.150 --> 00:44:34.750
So, it's an increasing age of public austerity
and there just isn't a sense that the government

00:44:34.750 --> 00:44:39.269
is going to be able to have the resources
to step in and have a vision for a green space.

00:44:39.269 --> 00:44:42.420
And so, I think what's exciting about the
High Line and hopefully what we're doing,

00:44:42.420 --> 00:44:50.250
is that a private-driven and community-led
approach to building a park is potentially

00:44:50.250 --> 00:44:51.420
the wave of the future.

00:44:51.420 --> 00:44:58.160
And is actually the way that parks will get
built and space will be saved for the public.

00:44:58.160 --> 00:45:05.030
&gt;&gt;MALE #5: What are you planning to do [inaudible]?

00:45:05.030 --> 00:45:06.030
[inaudible]?

00:45:06.030 --> 00:45:09.010
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: Well, I mean, when the sun
goes down these devices no longer produce

00:45:09.010 --> 00:45:10.599
any light.

00:45:10.599 --> 00:45:15.480
So, is the solution to just close it at dark,
or is the solution to actually supplement

00:45:15.480 --> 00:45:16.480
the light?

00:45:16.480 --> 00:45:20.859
I think that you will want to create a hybridized
system one way or another so you have the

00:45:20.859 --> 00:45:26.270
option, like some very high-powered LED's
or something built in-line to simulate maximum

00:45:26.270 --> 00:45:28.119
capacity of the sun when it's not out there.

00:45:28.119 --> 00:45:33.210
Like, on a really dark day, like the one we
had a couple days ago, I mean, it will be

00:45:33.210 --> 00:45:39.250
fairly dark down here and you don't get the
other ambient light that filters through the

00:45:39.250 --> 00:45:42.470
clouds in the sky, etc., like you do in an
above-ground space.

00:45:42.470 --> 00:45:44.150
So, I think it would be important to supplement--.

00:45:44.150 --> 00:45:47.160
At least have the ability to supplement that
light.

00:45:47.160 --> 00:45:49.190
&gt;&gt;MALE #5: You could simulate the night sky.

00:45:49.190 --> 00:45:50.710
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: Or you could just--.

00:45:50.710 --> 00:45:51.710
Ooh.

00:45:51.710 --> 00:45:55.799
Actually, if you just point this thing at
the sun at sunset, you will get a sunset.

00:45:55.799 --> 00:45:59.950
So, you'll get an orange and purple space,
which I think is kinda cool.

00:45:59.950 --> 00:46:07.240
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: The MTA made this weird promotional
video for the site.

00:46:07.240 --> 00:46:13.519
And in it, the MTA spokesman made a joke about
how it could become a nightclub, which was

00:46:13.519 --> 00:46:15.480
so weird coming from a public official.

00:46:15.480 --> 00:46:19.599
[laughter]
But one of the really fun things that we saw

00:46:19.599 --> 00:46:29.750
in the location on our tour was this abandoned
control tower, this weird little space, totally

00:46:29.750 --> 00:46:35.710
graffiti-full and you could tell people slept
in there over the years, and immediately we

00:46:35.710 --> 00:46:39.490
were like, "This would be an incredible say,
tree house, for kids.

00:46:39.490 --> 00:46:42.651
Or, just this really amazing space that could
be transformed into something really fun."

00:46:42.651 --> 00:46:45.562
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: Isn't it fun we're talking
about tree houses and the MTA is talking about

00:46:45.562 --> 00:46:46.562
a DJ booth?

00:46:46.562 --> 00:46:49.050
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: Clearly, they want the party

00:46:49.050 --> 00:46:50.619
to go on all night.

00:46:50.619 --> 00:46:55.130
But so, the possibility of what else could
happen down there.

00:46:55.130 --> 00:47:00.000
I mean, again, I think one of the things that
we need to be totally serious about is that

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:01.970
we do need a real business model.

00:47:01.970 --> 00:47:06.599
And there's a lot of different ways of thinking
about how we use the space during the day

00:47:06.599 --> 00:47:09.539
as well as the way we think about it during
the night.

00:47:09.539 --> 00:47:14.619
And the High Line has interestingly first
saved the space, and then built an amazing

00:47:14.619 --> 00:47:19.970
park, and they're now evolving a lot of their
approach to ways that they can stay in business

00:47:19.970 --> 00:47:21.030
as a park.

00:47:21.030 --> 00:47:26.559
The High Line needs to continue to raise money
in order to sustain itself as a private park.

00:47:26.559 --> 00:47:32.430
So, this will be hopefully the same sort of
model in which we'll need to, over time, continue

00:47:32.430 --> 00:47:33.430
to sustain ourselves.

00:47:33.430 --> 00:47:35.160
So, what is that business model?

00:47:35.160 --> 00:47:38.559
Maybe there are the opportunities to do nice
things in there at night.

00:47:38.559 --> 00:47:43.819
&gt;&gt;James Ramsey: I think it is noteworthy that
