00:48:20.249 --> 00:48:26.359
to the elderly, but I think you make a really
interesting point in that because it's underground,

00:48:26.359 --> 00:48:29.230
well, it never rains down there.

00:48:29.230 --> 00:48:30.589
It never snows down there.

00:48:30.589 --> 00:48:33.839
And the temperature is a very even 60-ish.

00:48:33.839 --> 00:48:37.390
And so, I think actually that's a really good
idea.

00:48:37.390 --> 00:48:45.039
I actually am not familiar with any sort of
organizations, specifically, in that neighborhood

00:48:45.039 --> 00:48:48.180
that we could reach out to wholesale, but
it's a good idea.

00:48:48.180 --> 00:48:52.220
&gt;&gt;Dan Barasch: Well, we've also heard a lot
about how young people would actually use

00:48:52.220 --> 00:48:53.220
the space.

00:48:53.220 --> 00:48:55.900
I mean, there's actually a lot of families.

00:48:55.900 --> 00:49:00.059
I mean, one of the great things about the
Lower East Side, and especially this whole

00:49:00.059 --> 00:49:04.420
corridor and this part of the Lower East Side,
is that it's really, really diverse.

00:49:04.420 --> 00:49:14.809
A lot of it is populated by people who are
on affordable or subsidized housing.

00:49:14.809 --> 00:49:17.539
And it's ethnically really diverse.

00:49:17.539 --> 00:49:22.789
And it has this really vibrant community that
takes care of itself because frankly, I think

00:49:22.789 --> 00:49:27.089
a lot of it is because people have lived there
for generations and the business community

00:49:27.089 --> 00:49:32.500
is very Mom and Pop and it has this community
feel.

00:49:32.500 --> 00:49:37.380
And yet, there's a sense that young people
don't really have a lot of green space.

00:49:37.380 --> 00:49:38.869
There's nowhere to go with kids.

00:49:38.869 --> 00:49:43.579
I mean, as a parent, where do you go with
your kids when it's not nice out on the weekends?

00:49:43.579 --> 00:49:47.430
And so, we've heard a lot of comments on how
people would use the space.

00:49:47.430 --> 00:49:51.329
And it's interesting 'cause this is actually
the first time, I think, that someone has

00:49:51.329 --> 00:49:54.990
suggested to us that old people would use
the space.

00:49:54.990 --> 00:49:56.242
I think it's exciting to think about that,
too.

00:49:56.242 --> 00:49:59.220
