00:55:56.559 --> 00:55:58.410
You know, that's the thing.

00:55:58.410 --> 00:56:00.849
And you're hitting the nail on the head.

00:56:00.849 --> 00:56:05.349
But just in researching this, I mean, you
can obviously concentrate light down and send

00:56:05.349 --> 00:56:08.710
it through just an empty shaft and send it
wherever you need it to go.

00:56:08.710 --> 00:56:11.180
It will require some pretty hardcore precision
to do that.

00:56:11.180 --> 00:56:16.619
So, you can, I think, feasibly do that for
a small amount of distance.

00:56:16.619 --> 00:56:21.720
But if you go into a fiber optic cable, there
is, of course, attenuation.

00:56:21.720 --> 00:56:26.640
And intercontinental cables under the sea
that transmit data or whatever, they have

00:56:26.640 --> 00:56:30.430
these boosters that help nudge things along.

00:56:30.430 --> 00:56:36.799
Obviously, we can't do that with the sun,
or else we're just paying for electricity.

00:56:36.799 --> 00:56:42.880
We have an attenuation that really puts our
limit on the fiber cables themselves at about,

00:56:42.880 --> 00:56:48.099
I don't know, like 20, 30, 40 meters, something
like that.

